{
  "case_id": "D2N132",
  "method": "cap_event",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nBack pain following a fall at a surprise birthday party.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports back pain following a fall at a surprise birthday party. He describes being crunched behind others while hiding, and then falling down a staircase railing. He states the pain started immediately after the fall and was exacerbated by twisting motions and lying flat. He denies any radicular symptoms or numbness in his legs. He has a history of lumbar fusion performed previously. He is currently taking ibuprofen for the pain and also takes medication for anxiety. He reports no other significant medical history.\n\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals tenderness to palpation over the lumbar region, particularly with rotation. Range of motion is limited due to pain. Neurological examination is unremarkable, with no reported numbness or tingling in the lower extremities. Examination does not reveal any signs of acute instability or nerve compression.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient's presentation is consistent with a lumbar strain secondary to trauma. The history of the fall and reported pain with rotation are concerning for muscle strain. The prior lumbar fusion is relevant to the overall clinical picture.\n\nPlan\nContinue ibuprofen 800mg three times daily with food. Recommend ice and heat alternating on the back. Encourage gentle movement and activity as tolerated. Follow up in one week if symptoms persist or worsen. Schedule a follow-up appointment in one week to assess progress and adjust treatment as needed.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nBack pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Lee is a 40-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of back pain. She states she was at a birthday party and she ran her back into the railing of the staircase and twisted her back. She denies any pain radiating down her legs. Lying flat and twisting motions aggravate the pain. She is currently taking ibuprofen.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nIbuprofen.\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nAnxiety.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nLumbar fusion\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the back shows range of motion without pain. Straight leg raise is negative. Sensation is intact.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the lumbar spine show no obvious signs of acute fracture. Evidence of a prior lumbar fusion with hardware in good position.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nLumbar spine strain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended ice and heat. She will continue with Motrin 800 mg 3 times a day with food. She will follow up with me as needed.",
